    <text id="B1073T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Jackson gives McDonnell an update on the case between James Carson and Joseph
                    Harrison, which remains to be settled since Carson refuses to pay.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    Bureau of Refugees, Freedmen and Abandoned Lands,<lb/>Office 4th Division, 9th
                    Sub-District, Virginia,
                    <name type="recipient"><abbr expan="Captain">Capt.</abbr> John A.
                            McDonnell<lb/><abbr expan="Sub Assistant Commissioner">Sub Asst.
                        Comr</abbr><lb/>Winchester</name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1867-07-24">July 24 1867</date>
                        <name type="place">Staunton, <abbr expan="Virginia">Va.</abbr></name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Captain</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>I respectfully <add hand="h1" place="inline">forward</add> copy of Record of
                    Board of Agents sitting at Staunton <abbr expan="June 28, 1866">June
                    28/66</abbr> and copy of a letter addressed to James E. Carson receipt of which
                    he acknowledged by calling at this office and promising to settle which he has
                    not done and I learn does not intend to do.</p>

                <p>Joseph Harrison (<abbr expan="colored">c</abbr>) who is poor states he has no
                    means to sue in County Court <abbr expan="amount">amt.</abbr> being in excess of
                    a Magistrates Court jurisdiction that he fears even these he should not have a
                    fair verdict and further he understands Carson will plead benefit of
                        <unclear>Stay</unclear> Law and as judgement by Board of Agents was rendered
                    in his favor while the said Board was empowered by the military to hear and
                    adjudge on such cases, he <unclear>asks</unclear> an order from the <abbr
                        expan="Major General">Maj. Genl.</abbr>
                    <unclear>Com<hi rend="super">anding</hi></unclear> to enforce the judgement in
                    his favor for <abbr expan="$35.95">$35 95/100</abbr> with Interest to <abbr
                        expan="June 1, 1866">June 1/66</abbr>
                    <abbr expan="$5.11">$5 11/100</abbr> &amp; <abbr expan="Interest"
                    >Int.</abbr> on <abbr expan="$35.95">$35 95/100</abbr> from <abbr
                        expan="June 1, 1866">June 1/66</abbr> to date of Settlement. Carson is an
                    old slave dealer <pb n="2"/>and was a bitter rebel. He is abundantly able to pay
                    at any time, and an order in his case would cause prompt settlement of several
                    claims made by Freedmen through this office which they have not the means to
                    prosecute in the courts.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        <abbr expan="Your obedient servant">Yr. obt. servt</abbr>
                    </salute>
                    <signed><hi rend="underline">Thos P Jackson</hi><lb/>Agent</signed>
                    <seg type="postscript">one enclosure</seg>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
